y-first-century incarnation of this old genre. Clawson finds that in order for Sacred Harp singers to maintain the bond forged by their love of music, they must grapple with a host of difficult issues, including how to maintain the authenticity of their tradition and how to carefully negotiate the tensions created by their disparate cultural, religious, and political beliefs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFolk music -- Religious aspects -- Baptists. 0aFolk music festivals -- United States. 0aFolk music festivalszUnited States. 0aFolk musicxReligious aspectsxBaptists. 0aSacred vocal music -- Social aspects -- United States. 0aSacred vocal musicxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aShape-note singing -- Social aspects -- United States. 0aShape-note singingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  acommunal, community, culture, cultural, spiritual, spirituality, traditional, tradition, sacred, harp, instrumental, singers, song, music, musical, choral, america, american, united states, usa, 19th century, south, southern, a cappella, alabama, fieldwork, georgia, chicago, minneapolis, hollywood, performance, art, artistic, contemporary, modern, present day, genre, folk.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226109633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226109633/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles